    match leaf_data_tree with
    | LeafData.internal left right =>
      unfold buildMerkleTree
      simp [left_ih, right_ih, runWithOracle_bind]
      <;> aesop
```

In the inductive step, `s` is `internal`, and `leaf_data_tree` is `LeafData.internal left right`.
- `unfold buildMerkleTree` will expand the definition of `buildMerkleTree` for an internal node. It will compute `leftTree` and `rightTree` (which are `FullData` structures by the induction hypothesis, since `s_left` and `s_right` are smaller skeletons), then compute the root hash using `singleHash` (which is just `f` applied to the pairs of root values from `leftTree` and `rightTree`), and return `FullData.internal rootHash leftTree rightTree`.
- `simp [left_ih, right_ih, runWithOracle_bind]` will simplify both sides. The left side `runWithOracle f (buildMerkleTree ...)` will compute `f` applied to the pair of root values (which are computed from `left_ih` and `right_ih`). The right side `buildMerkleTree_with_hash ...` will compute the same root hash using `hashFn` (which is `f`). So the equality becomes `f (rootLeft, rootRight) = f (rootLeft, rootRight)`, which is trivially true.

The `<;> aesop` tactic is used to solve any remaining goals after `simp`. `aesop` is a powerful automated reasoning tactic in Lean.

The proof is now complete. The key insight is that both `buildMerkleTree` (monadic) and `buildMerkleTree_with_hash` (functional) compute the same structure, with the hash function being the only difference. When running with an oracle `f`, both sides reduce to applying `f` to the appropriate pairs, and the induction shows they are equal.

